    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle is organized according to classical MBSE abstraction layers: (1) **Requirements** – traceable stakeholder needs expressed in natural‑language or SysML requirements blocks; (2) **Functional architecture** – SysML activity or sequence diagrams that decompose high‑level functions into observable interactions; (3) **Logical architecture** – a component‑connector model built with SysML IBDs, ACME or AADL that specifies interfaces and data flows; (4) **Product/Technical layer** – a concrete Instantiation of the logical model in a target platform (e.g., a Simulink block‑set, C++/Java classes, or a MontiArc simulation model). Transitions between layers are governed by traceability links that map requirements to functional activities, functional blocks to logical components, and logical interfaces to concrete implementation objects. Governance is achieved through a MBSE “Requirements‑Functions‑Logics‑Physics” (RFLP) workflow, ensuring that any change at the requirement level propagates automatically downwards via version‑controlled SysML models and that any prototype‑level behaviour is validated before promotion to the next abstraction tier.*"
]

